The Pumpkins Example

Alexandra Chronopoulou

LEcture 13

The Chicago Pumpkins Data Set

The pumpkins.csv data set contains information regarding the size and price of pumpkins sold in the Chicago area. Our goal in this example is to predict the size of the pumpkin (response) based on its price (predictor).

pumpkins = read.csv("chicagopumpkins.csv",header=TRUE)
dim(pumpkins)
## [1] 248   2

We start by plotting the data:

plot(pumpkins$price, pumpkins$size, pch=20, xlab="Pumpkin's Price", ylab="Pumpkins' Size")

We see that a linear fit is probably not a good idea. Indeed,

model = lm(size ~ price, data=pumpkins)
summary(model)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = size ~ price, data = pumpkins)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -1.6272 -0.7594  0.2244  0.3728  2.8245 
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 0.5948315  0.0988339   6.018 6.35e-09 ***
## price       0.0096781  0.0006856  14.117  < 2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.9477 on 246 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.4475, Adjusted R-squared:  0.4453 
## F-statistic: 199.3 on 1 and 246 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Although the predictor is significant at explaining the response, the \(R^2\) is on the lower end and the scatter plot does not support a straight line as a good fit.

So, we are going to use polynomial regression.

Polynomials Regression

The model we want to fit looks as follows: \[y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x + \beta_2 x^2 + \ldots + \beta_d x^d + \varepsilon_i\]

So, we need to select \(d\). We start with a Forward Selection approach. That is we start by a linear model, and we keep adding terms until the added term becomes statistically insignificant.

# Forward Selection
model0 =  lm(size ~ price , data=pumpkins)
summary(model0)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = size ~ price, data = pumpkins)

We see that the 5th order model has a 5th order term with \(p\)-value equal to 0.0519, which is higher than 5%, so we conclude that the optimal order for the polynomial, according to the forward selection method is \(d=4\). So, the fitted model is: \[\hat{y}_i = \hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_1 x + \hat{\beta}_2 x^2 + \hat{\beta}_3 x^4 + \hat{\beta}_4 x^4 \]

If we plot all the fitted models, we have:

newprice = data.frame(price=seq(17, 255, 1))
plot(pumpkins$price, pumpkins$size, pch=20, ylim=c(0,5), xlab="Pumpkin's Price", ylab="Pumpkins' Size", main="Forward Selection Models")
lines(newprice$price, predict(model1, newprice), col="blue", lty=1, lwd=2);
lines(newprice$price, predict(model2, newprice), col="orange", lty=1, lwd=2);
lines(newprice$price, predict(model3, newprice), col="magenta", lty=1, lwd=2);
lines(newprice$price, predict(model4, newprice), col="green", lty=1, lwd=2);
legend(210, 0.75, legend=c("d=2", "d=3", "d=4", "d=5"),
       col=c("blue", "orange", "magenta", "green"), lty=c(1,1,1,1), cex=0.8, lwd=c(2,2,2,2))

The magenta line is the one that corresponds to the 4th order model.

We can also select \(d\) using the Backward Elimination approach. So, we start with a large value for \(d\) and we eliminate terms until all the terms in the model are statistically significant:

model_1 =  lm(size ~ price + I(price^2) + I(price^3) + I(price^4)+ I(price^5)+ I(price^6) + I(price^7)+ I(price^8)+ I(price^9)+ I(price^10), data=pumpkins)

Starting with an order 10 model, we identify that an 8th order model is optimal according to the backward elimination criterion. If we plot all the fitted models, we have:

newprice = data.frame(price=seq(17, 255, 1))
plot(pumpkins$price, pumpkins$size, ylim=c(0,5), pch=20, xlab="Pumpkin's Price", ylab="Pumpkins' Size", main="Backward Selection Models")
lines(newprice$price, predict(model_1, newprice), col="blue", lty=2, lwd=2);
lines(newprice$price, predict(model_2, newprice), col="orange", lty=2, lwd=2);
lines(newprice$price, predict(model_3, newprice), col="magenta", lty=2, lwd=2);
legend(210, 0.5, legend=c("d=10", "d=9", "d=8"),
       col=c("blue", "orange", "magenta"), lty=c(2,2,2), cex=0.8, lwd=2)

The magenta line is the one that corresponds to the 8th order model.

Orthogonal Polynomials

We discussed that when there is a need to fit higher order polynomials, our results might be unstable. For that reason, it is preferred to work with orthogonal polynomials, that is polynomials whose coefficients inner product is zero.

In R, we can do this using the poly functions. In the code below, we repeat the same process as above (for choosing \(d\)) using the orthogonal polynomials.

# Forward Selection
model1s =  lm(size ~ poly(price,2), data=pumpkins)
summary(model1s)

Splines Regression

Now, let’s try to use different types of Splines basis to fit the pumpkins’ data.

B-Splines

We start by fitting a model with B-splines with df=5. Note that we choose intercept=FALSE (the default) inside the bs function, because an intercept will be automatically added by the lm function. If we choose intercept=TRUE, then R will not be able to estimate two intercepts and will procude NAs .

library(splines)
pumpkin.bs = lm(size ~ bs(price, df=5, intercept=FALSE), data=pumpkins)

K-Fold Cross Validation

Last, we are going to use R in order to select the optimal number of knots via K-fold cross validation.

The caret library contain a function that allows us to easily create \(k\) folds from our data.

library(caret)
## Warning: package 'caret' was built under R version 3.6.2
## Loading required package: ggplot2
## Warning: package 'ggplot2' was built under R version 3.6.2
## Loading required package: lattice
## Warning: package 'lattice' was built under R version 3.6.2
   CV_K =c() # initialize the vector to store the CV(k) errors for every fixed knot selection
  
  for (knots in 3:7) {  # we start with 3 knots and go up to 7 knots
 
    j=knots-2 # counter index starting at 1
    MSE_i = c()
    
    for (k in 3:10){   # loop over the number of folds in the data
      i=k-2 # counter index starting at 1
      folds <- createFolds(pumpkins$price, k) # Create the folds
  
      # Function that fits the model,  computes the MSE of every fold
      results = lapply(folds, function(x){
        pumpkin_train = pumpkins[-x,] # Create train set for fold "x"
        pumpkin_test = pumpkins[x,] # Create corresponding test set.
        pumpkin.bs = lm(size ~ bs(price, knots, intercept=FALSE), data=pumpkin_train) # Fit the model in the train set
        pumpkin.pred = predict(pumpkin.bs, newdata=pumpkin_test) # Test the model in the test set
        mserror = mean( (pumpkin_test$size-pumpkin.pred)^2) # Compute the MSEi for every fold
        return(mserror)
     })
     MSE_i[i] = mean(unlist(results))  # Repeat the previous steps k times
    }
    
    CV_K[j] = mean(MSE_i) # This is the CV_k for j+2 knots
  }
 
   CV_K 
## [1] 0.5232160 0.4918207 0.4713699 0.4685606 0.4692828
NumberOfKnots = which.min(CV_K) +2
NumberOfKnots
## [1] 6
